WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:12.930 --> 00:00:16.000
Professor Paul Bloom:
Two follow-ups on

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:19.140
yesterday's--I'm sorry,
on Monday's lecture.

00:00:19.140 --> 00:00:24.667
One is that somebody came up
after class and asked when the

00:00:24.667 --> 00:00:30.195
preference for your own language
emerges in development and

00:00:30.195 --> 00:00:33.422
fortunately,
studies pretty much exactly

00:00:33.422 --> 00:00:35.630
this sort of infant
understanding.

00:00:35.630 --> 00:00:38.919
She knew the answer.
There's been studies looking at

00:00:38.919 --> 00:00:42.848
newborn babies finding that
pretty much the moment they pop

00:00:42.848 --> 00:00:45.761
out they favor their own
language over other

00:00:45.761 --> 00:00:49.970
language--over other languages.
And this suggests that they are

00:00:49.970 --> 00:00:52.425
listening while in utero,
while in the womb,

00:00:52.425 --> 00:00:55.166
to the rhythms of their
language and developing a

00:00:55.166 --> 00:00:57.936
preference for it.
A second issue is,

00:00:57.936 --> 00:01:02.712
I talked very briefly about a
court case in which the person

00:01:02.712 --> 00:01:07.406
was--said at a moment where
someone else was pointing a gun

00:01:07.406 --> 00:01:10.640
at a police officer,
"Let him have it!"

00:01:10.640 --> 00:01:14.284
and a police officer was killed.
And that person was charged

00:01:14.284 --> 00:01:17.747
with murder but I admitted I
didn't actually know how things

00:01:17.747 --> 00:01:21.209
turned out and was kind enough
to do extensive research.

00:01:21.209 --> 00:01:24.517
Well, he went to Wikipedia and
[laughter]

00:01:24.517 --> 00:01:28.667
found out the answer.
The answer is he was tried and

00:01:28.667 --> 00:01:33.137
found guilty for murder.
He was then subsequently

00:01:33.137 --> 00:01:36.970
pardoned.
In fact, he was pardoned in

00:01:36.970 --> 00:01:42.980
1988, which is really nice
except he was executed in 1957.

00:01:42.980 --> 00:01:47.270
But they did it into a movie.
So, it's a movie.

00:01:47.270 --> 00:01:49.789
Okay.
So, I want to do today,

00:01:49.789 --> 00:01:52.194
for the first part of the
lecture, is continue the

00:01:52.194 --> 00:01:54.354
language lecture and then move
to perception,

00:01:54.354 --> 00:01:57.675
attention, and memory.
And what we had spoken about

00:01:57.675 --> 00:02:01.310
was--We first talked about
universals of language,

00:02:01.310 --> 00:02:05.575
then moved to some detail about
the different aspects of

00:02:05.575 --> 00:02:09.780
language including phonology,
morphology, and syntax.

00:02:09.780 --> 00:02:13.982
We discussed the ways in which
language does the amazing things

00:02:13.982 --> 00:02:17.981
it does, including the fact that
language has used arbitrary

00:02:17.981 --> 00:02:20.759
science or sounds to convey
concepts,

00:02:20.759 --> 00:02:25.104
and that languages exploit a
combinatorial system including

00:02:25.104 --> 00:02:29.224
recursion to put together these
symbols into a virtually

00:02:29.224 --> 00:02:32.370
limitless set of meaningful
sentences.

00:02:32.370 --> 00:02:35.219
We then talked about
development and made some

00:02:35.219 --> 00:02:39.018
remarks about the developmental
time course – talking about

00:02:39.018 --> 00:02:42.817
the emergence of language from
babies to – where babies are

00:02:42.817 --> 00:02:46.490
really good at learning language
to you who are not,

00:02:46.490 --> 00:02:52.973
whose brains have atrophied,
whose language capacities are

00:02:52.973 --> 00:02:55.723
dead.
Final issue is to shift to

00:02:55.723 --> 00:02:58.625
animals.
Now that we know something

00:02:58.625 --> 00:03:02.305
about language,
we could then ask do animals

00:03:02.305 --> 00:03:05.900
use--possess the same sort of
language?

00:03:05.900 --> 00:03:09.050
And if not, can they learn it?
Now, there is absolutely no

00:03:09.050 --> 00:03:12.758
doubt at all that nonhuman
animals possess communication

00:03:12.758 --> 00:03:16.053
systems.
This has been known forever and

00:03:16.053 --> 00:03:20.059
is not a matter of controversy.
And if you want to use the term

00:03:20.059 --> 00:03:22.268
"language" to mean
"communication," then the answer

00:03:22.268 --> 00:03:25.384
is obviously "yes."
Dogs and bees and monkeys have

00:03:25.384 --> 00:03:28.245
language.
If you want to use language

00:03:28.245 --> 00:03:32.855
though in the more technical,
narrow sense as anything that

00:03:32.855 --> 00:03:36.669
has the properties that we
discussed earlier,

00:03:36.669 --> 00:03:39.780
using English and ASL and
Spanish and so on as our

00:03:39.780 --> 00:03:42.889
background, the answer's almost
certainly "no."

00:03:42.889 --> 00:03:47.023
Animal communication systems
fall into sort of one of three

00:03:47.023 --> 00:03:49.853
categories.
Either there is a finite list

00:03:49.853 --> 00:03:52.543
of calls, so vervet monkeys,
for instance,

00:03:52.543 --> 00:03:56.416
have a small list of calls to
convey different warnings like

00:03:56.416 --> 00:03:59.960
"attack from a snake" or "attack
from a leopard."

00:03:59.960 --> 00:04:02.460
There is a continuous analog
signal.

00:04:02.460 --> 00:04:04.298
So, bee dance,
for instance,

00:04:04.298 --> 00:04:06.984
works on this way.
Bee dance communicates the

00:04:06.984 --> 00:04:09.429
location of food sources but
doesn't do it in any

00:04:09.429 --> 00:04:12.538
syntactically structured way.
Rather, the intensity of the

00:04:12.538 --> 00:04:15.389
dance corresponds to the
richness of the food source.

00:04:15.389 --> 00:04:19.212
And then, you get things like
random variation on a theme such

00:04:19.212 --> 00:04:22.502
as birdsong.
But what you don't find in any

00:04:22.502 --> 00:04:25.961
real sense is phonology,
morphology, syntax,

00:04:25.961 --> 00:04:29.500
combinatorial systems or
arbitrary names.

00:04:29.500 --> 00:04:32.660
Now, this much is not
particularly controversial.

00:04:32.660 --> 00:04:35.089
There gets to be a lot of
controversy though.

00:04:35.089 --> 00:04:37.560
This is the summary about
nonhuman communication systems.

00:04:37.560 --> 00:04:42.995
It gets more controversial when
we get to famous cases of

00:04:42.995 --> 00:04:47.170
primates trained by humans such
as Kanzi,

00:04:47.170 --> 00:04:50.570
Nim Chimpsky,
and other famous primates that

00:04:50.570 --> 00:04:55.000
you may well have seen on the
Discovery channel and other

00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:56.933
venues.
And this is fairly

00:04:56.933 --> 00:05:00.035
controversial.
If you read the Gray textbook,

00:05:00.035 --> 00:05:03.579
while nothing in it is
particularly inaccurate,

00:05:03.579 --> 00:05:06.628
I think Gray is actually a
little bit too credulous,

00:05:06.628 --> 00:05:09.976
too believing in the claims
that have been made about the

00:05:09.976 --> 00:05:13.658
abilities of the animals.
So many scientists argue,

00:05:13.658 --> 00:05:16.543
for instance,
that animals like Kanzi,

00:05:16.543 --> 00:05:20.597
even if they can be said to be
learning words at all,

00:05:20.597 --> 00:05:24.870
learn very few of them.
And it takes them extensive

00:05:24.870 --> 00:05:29.129
years of training to learn,
unlike a normally developing

00:05:29.129 --> 00:05:33.930
child who could learn a word in
a day or a word in an hour.

00:05:33.930 --> 00:05:38.594
The utterances often have order
but this order tends to be very

00:05:38.594 --> 00:05:41.980
limited and lacks the recursive
properties.

00:05:41.980 --> 00:05:44.794
And in fact,
the lack of recursion is not

00:05:44.794 --> 00:05:48.343
controversial.
Finally, the utterances of

00:05:48.343 --> 00:05:54.308
chimpanzees--trained chimpanzees
are extremely repetitive so what

00:05:54.308 --> 00:05:59.155
you often see on TV and in
documentaries is sort of a

00:05:59.155 --> 00:06:02.353
sampling.
And the sampling could often be

00:06:02.353 --> 00:06:06.140
very impressive but if you take
just what they say at random it

00:06:06.140 --> 00:06:09.526
tends to look like this.
This is typical chimpanzee

00:06:09.526 --> 00:06:13.000
utterances just taken at random:
"Nim eat, Nim eat.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:16.640
Drink, eat, me Nim.
Me gum, me gum.

00:06:16.640 --> 00:06:20.139
Tickle me, Nim play.
Me eat, me eat.

00:06:20.139 --> 00:06:22.680
Me banana, you banana,
me you give.

00:06:22.680 --> 00:06:26.003
Banana me, me eat.
Give orange,

00:06:26.003 --> 00:06:29.189
me give, eat orange,
me eat orange."

00:06:29.189 --> 00:06:33.995
Lila Gleitman once commented
that if any normally developing

00:06:33.995 --> 00:06:37.905
child spoke like this,
his parents would rush him

00:06:37.905 --> 00:06:42.283
screaming to a neurologist.
There's a broader question

00:06:42.283 --> 00:06:45.277
here, which is,
"Why would we ever expect a

00:06:45.277 --> 00:06:48.199
chimpanzee to learn a human
language?"

00:06:48.199 --> 00:06:52.638
We don't normally expect one
species to have the capacities

00:06:52.638 --> 00:06:57.363
associated with another species.
So, bats use echolocation to

00:06:57.363 --> 00:07:01.079
get around and some birds
navigate by the stars,

00:07:01.079 --> 00:07:04.337
but there's not an active
research program seeing if cats

00:07:04.337 --> 00:07:07.769
can use echolocation or dogs
could navigate by the stars.

00:07:07.769 --> 00:07:10.795
And I think one reason why you
might be tempted to think,

00:07:10.795 --> 00:07:13.875
"well, of course chimps must be
able to learn language" is

00:07:13.875 --> 00:07:16.955
because you might be caught in
the grips of some bad ideas

00:07:16.955 --> 00:07:20.311
about language.
So, one idea is you might say,

00:07:20.311 --> 00:07:22.139
"Look.
Chimps should use language

00:07:22.139 --> 00:07:26.521
because chimps are so smart."
But the response to this is,

00:07:26.521 --> 00:07:32.060
"they are smart but we know
that smart isn't enough."

00:07:32.060 --> 00:07:35.901
We know that the human capacity
for language is not totally a

00:07:35.901 --> 00:07:38.906
result of smartness.
There are smart children who,

00:07:38.906 --> 00:07:41.438
due to some deficit in their
language capacity,

00:07:41.438 --> 00:07:43.639
don't speak or understand a
language.

00:07:43.639 --> 00:07:46.439
So, the smartness of
chimpanzees does not in itself

00:07:46.439 --> 00:07:49.629
demonstrate that they should be
able to learn language.

00:07:49.629 --> 00:07:51.897
You might also point out
correctly that chimps are our

00:07:51.897 --> 00:07:54.549
nearest evolutionary relatives,
which is right,

00:07:54.549 --> 00:07:58.763
so you--one would expect on the
face of it--it's not

00:07:58.763 --> 00:08:03.473
unreasonable to expect us to
share a lot of abilities with

00:08:03.473 --> 00:08:05.649
them.
On the other hand,

00:08:05.649 --> 00:08:09.846
we split from them a long time
ago and plainly humans are

00:08:09.846 --> 00:08:13.532
different from chimps.
And there was five million

00:08:13.532 --> 00:08:17.925
years either way and that's more
than enough time for a language

00:08:17.925 --> 00:08:22.205
capacity to evolve.
Now, none of this is to say

00:08:22.205 --> 00:08:27.594
that the study of nonhuman
communication systems isn't

00:08:27.594 --> 00:08:30.794
interesting.
From my own--This is my

00:08:30.794 --> 00:08:33.269
personal opinion I'll raise
here.

00:08:33.269 --> 00:08:36.456
From my own opinion,
the study of the attempts to

00:08:36.456 --> 00:08:39.709
try to teach chimpanzees,
or gibbons, or gorillas,

00:08:39.709 --> 00:08:42.629
a human language like ASL are
misguided.

00:08:42.629 --> 00:08:46.274
It would be as if a team of
monkeys kidnapped a human child

00:08:46.274 --> 00:08:49.480
and tried to train him how to
hoot like a monkey.

00:08:49.480 --> 00:08:52.552
It might be enjoyable but it
does not seem to give us any

00:08:52.552 --> 00:08:54.854
rich insights.
What I think is a lot more

00:08:54.854 --> 00:08:57.759
interesting is the study of
these animal communication

00:08:57.759 --> 00:09:00.822
systems in the wild.
There's a linguistics of human

00:09:00.822 --> 00:09:04.428
language that has delineated the
principles that underlie all

00:09:04.428 --> 00:09:07.446
human languages.
It would be as extraordinarily

00:09:07.446 --> 00:09:11.325
interesting to attempt the same
linguistic program to the other

00:09:11.325 --> 00:09:14.953
communication systems used in
the wild such as the cries of

00:09:14.953 --> 00:09:18.657
vervet monkeys and bee dance.
So, this brings the section on

00:09:18.657 --> 00:09:21.655
language to a close but I want
to tell you a few things we

00:09:21.655 --> 00:09:24.099
didn't talk about.
One of the problems with an

00:09:24.099 --> 00:09:27.075
Intro Psych course is we have to
whip through a lot of topics

00:09:27.075 --> 00:09:29.165
very fast.
So, if you were to take a

00:09:29.165 --> 00:09:32.519
course that focused directly on
language you might learn,

00:09:32.519 --> 00:09:34.347
for instance,
more about language in the

00:09:34.347 --> 00:09:37.252
brain, something touched about
very briefly in the textbook but

00:09:37.252 --> 00:09:40.110
something that has a large
literature associated with it.

00:09:40.110 --> 00:09:44.446
Similarly, and related to this,
there's language disorders,

00:09:44.446 --> 00:09:48.856
disorders like aphasias and
disorders like specific language

00:09:48.856 --> 00:09:52.292
impairment and dyslexia.
There is the study of language

00:09:52.292 --> 00:09:54.943
perception and production.
How is it that we do this

00:09:54.943 --> 00:09:58.004
amazing feat of understanding
and producing words in a

00:09:58.004 --> 00:10:01.547
fraction of a second?
Where does that ability come

00:10:01.547 --> 00:10:03.815
from?
There is the study of reading

00:10:03.815 --> 00:10:07.052
which is, in many ways,
different from the study of a

00:10:07.052 --> 00:10:10.167
language.
Remember when Darwin described

00:10:10.167 --> 00:10:13.753
language as an instinct.
He carefully distinguished it

00:10:13.753 --> 00:10:16.868
from other things that don't
come natural to us including

00:10:16.868 --> 00:10:18.270
reading.
And in fact,

00:10:18.270 --> 00:10:20.788
reading is difficult.
Reading is a cultural

00:10:20.788 --> 00:10:22.570
invention, not every human has
it.

00:10:22.570 --> 00:10:25.346
And unlike language,
reading is acquired with

00:10:25.346 --> 00:10:27.870
tremendous difficulty over many
years.

00:10:27.870 --> 00:10:30.728
On the other hand,
reading plainly intersects with

00:10:30.728 --> 00:10:32.975
language.
It's a new way of conveying

00:10:32.975 --> 00:10:35.649
language, moving out from speech
to writing.

00:10:35.649 --> 00:10:39.220
And the psychology and
neuroscience of reading is thus

00:10:39.220 --> 00:10:42.244
very interesting.
There's bilingualism and

00:10:42.244 --> 00:10:45.602
multilingualism.
The questions people in this

00:10:45.602 --> 00:10:50.225
room typically are going to be
interested in is does it matter

00:10:50.225 --> 00:10:54.849
for how well you learn language
whether you're learning one or

00:10:54.849 --> 00:10:58.837
two or three or four.
How is it that a multilingual

00:10:58.837 --> 00:11:03.080
encodes all these different
languages inside a single brain?

00:11:03.080 --> 00:11:07.878
And so on.
Finally, a very hot issue is

00:11:07.878 --> 00:11:12.224
that of the relationship between
language and thought and I'm

00:11:12.224 --> 00:11:16.426
actually--A few years ago I
taught an entire seminar called

00:11:16.426 --> 00:11:20.990
"Language and Thought" devoted
to precisely this question.

00:11:20.990 --> 00:11:24.425
And it's a cool question and it
could break up into two very

00:11:24.425 --> 00:11:27.333
general questions.
One is, "Is language necessary

00:11:27.333 --> 00:11:30.361
for abstract thought?"
And one way to answer that

00:11:30.361 --> 00:11:34.526
question is to look at creatures
without language like babies and

00:11:34.526 --> 00:11:37.259
chimpanzees and see how smart
they are.

00:11:37.259 --> 00:11:39.541
It might be that they're
not--that they're very smart,

00:11:39.541 --> 00:11:41.995
in which case it would suggest
you don't need language for

00:11:41.995 --> 00:11:43.787
abstract thought.
On the other hand,

00:11:43.787 --> 00:11:46.548
it might be that they have
certain cognitive limitations,

00:11:46.548 --> 00:11:48.965
which would suggest that
language is essential for

00:11:48.965 --> 00:11:51.624
abstract thought.
Then there's the related

00:11:51.624 --> 00:11:53.954
question.
Even once you know a language,

00:11:53.954 --> 00:11:57.247
does the structural properties
of the language that you know

00:11:57.247 --> 00:12:00.702
affect the way you think?
And the claim that the language

00:12:00.702 --> 00:12:04.061
you know affects how you think
is sometimes described as

00:12:04.061 --> 00:12:07.419
linguistic relativity or the
Sapir-Whorf hypothesis.

00:12:07.419 --> 00:12:09.741
So for instance,
there's a lot of research

00:12:09.741 --> 00:12:13.364
looking at speakers of different
languages such as English versus

00:12:13.364 --> 00:12:16.535
Korean and seeing whether
structural differences in these

00:12:16.535 --> 00:12:19.966
languages affect how you think.
Now, some of this work is

00:12:19.966 --> 00:12:22.960
discussed in the readings,
the book--the Gray textbook,

00:12:22.960 --> 00:12:26.813
and the selections from The
Norton Anthology. And this

00:12:26.813 --> 00:12:29.687
makes up--again,
I've showed this to you on

00:12:29.687 --> 00:12:33.584
Monday--your reading response
where you have to address this

00:12:33.584 --> 00:12:37.020
question and take your best shot
at answering it.

00:12:40.080 --> 00:12:42.110
What are your questions about
language?

00:12:54.100 --> 00:13:00.480
Yes.
Student: [inaudible]

00:13:00.480 --> 00:13:06.360
Professor Paul Bloom:
The question was raised,

00:13:06.360 --> 00:13:09.873
"Some people learn languages
easier than others and how do we

00:13:09.873 --> 00:13:13.042
explain this?"
And the answer is you could ask

00:13:13.042 --> 00:13:17.508
the question both with regard to
first language learning – so

00:13:17.508 --> 00:13:20.750
some children learn language
very quickly,

00:13:20.750 --> 00:13:23.774
some are very slow – and also
with regard to second language

00:13:23.774 --> 00:13:25.659
learning.
Some of you are breezing

00:13:25.659 --> 00:13:28.730
through your second language
requirement here at Yale.

00:13:28.730 --> 00:13:31.809
Others are struggling and
miserable.

00:13:31.809 --> 00:13:34.360
And there's considerable
variation.

00:13:34.360 --> 00:13:37.950
There's the story of Einstein
who was very slow to learn

00:13:37.950 --> 00:13:41.409
language and didn't speak at all
until he was four.

00:13:41.409 --> 00:13:43.709
And in fact,
he was a--He said his first

00:13:43.709 --> 00:13:46.952
words when all of a sudden he
was having supper with his

00:13:46.952 --> 00:13:49.900
parents and he put down the
spoon and he said,

00:13:49.900 --> 00:13:54.182
"The soup is too hot."
And his parents stared in

00:13:54.182 --> 00:13:56.860
astonishment and said,
"You've never spoken before."

00:13:56.860 --> 00:14:01.658
And he said,
"Well, up to now everything's

00:14:01.658 --> 00:14:04.204
been fine."
[laughter]

00:14:04.204 --> 00:14:07.285
It's not a true story.
[laughter]

00:14:07.285 --> 00:14:11.421
The question of why and where
these differences come from,

00:14:11.421 --> 00:14:15.049
nobody really knows and it's
surprisingly hard.

00:14:15.049 --> 00:14:18.340
There's a slight advantage for
being female.

00:14:18.340 --> 00:14:21.403
Girls are slightly more
advanced in language than boys

00:14:21.403 --> 00:14:24.814
but it's not a big one and you
need a hundred people to just

00:14:24.814 --> 00:14:29.250
see it statistically.
There's a big genetic factor.

00:14:29.250 --> 00:14:32.032
If your parents learned
language quickly and learned

00:14:32.032 --> 00:14:34.759
other languages quickly,
you are more likely to.

00:14:34.759 --> 00:14:39.099
But an understanding of the
brain bases of these differences

00:14:39.099 --> 00:14:43.585
or the cognitive bases or the
social bases is just--is largely

00:14:43.585 --> 00:14:46.450
an open question.
Yes.

00:14:46.450 --> 00:14:50.123
Student: What happens
when parents [inaudible]

